{"key":"processedPost-6407581","value":{"id":6407581,"first":6406785,"last":11591536,"when":1167412047,"utime":"12/29/06 07:07 PM","content":"Perlite works excellent in a casing layer in the large, course size.  It works not by holding water, but by preventing clumping and providing lots of air pockets in the layer itself, which stimulates primordia.  By mixing perlite with vermiculite, you get the best of both worlds. . .moisture retention in the verm, and air retention in the perlite.  Ph balancing isn't necessary unless you add peat, which isn't absolutely required for cubes.  Just don't try to grow agaricus or other edibles without peat in the mix, because they won't pin.<br />RR","title":"Re: PERLITE (in a casing layer)"}}